					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">kyuusaku wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">you'd have to give it more RAM and a FPGA to cover CHR bankswitching unless the card can be written at a speed of 12KiB/Vblank to emulate bankswitching.</div>
<br />A data rate of 12 KiB every 1/60 s is less than 1 MB per second, well under the limit of classic PCI or even USB. Yes, this assumes that VRAM is writable while rendering is on. That can be solved: steal a cycle from sprite processing like the GBA does.
<br />
<br />But seriously, ArcadeVGA is probably the way to go if you want to send 240p or 288p video to a CRT. Are there any cheap circuits for turning ArcadeVGA's RGB output into YPP ("component") output for TVs?</div>

